I thought my local French bakery had the best croissant until I tried Tartine. All I can say is OMG just order everything. Any thoughts of dieting leave at the front door. The croissants are huge and airy with the perfect ratio of chewy and flaky. Of course the chocolate ones are even better. The morning bun is sweet with an essence of orange. If you want to go all out citrus the sesame orange tea cake is amazing and vegan! Their gluten free muffins are moist and filling. The chocolate oat cookie is everything you want It to be. But the star here is the banana cream pie with that crazy flaky crust, rich caramel and dark chocolate, the perfect creme anglaise and some fluffy whipped cream with dark chocolate shavings on top.

Tartine is one of those quintessential SF places that you just have to stop by if you're visiting. I don't know much about the history of the place, but I do know it's ridiculously famous and that the lines are crazy long almost always. Is it worth the long lines? Keep reading to find out.. Some famous places are overpriced, overhyped, and frankly don't serve great food. Tartine, while overpriced (but what isn't overpriced in the city), actually serves excellent baked goods in my opinion. I have been here twice (once at night and once in the morning, both times on weekends), and been very pleased with my food. The bakery itself is not very large. There are probably 8-10 tables inside crammed in really close to each other. You order at the counter after your eyes have feasted on all of their delectable offerings. They have a variety of pastries, tarts, croissants, and even croque monsieur. I have tried their bread pudding, chocolate and hazelnut tart, apple pie, and smoked ham and gruyere croissant and liked each item. I'd probably get all of them again except for the apple pie. It's not bad, it's just not as good as all the other things I've tried. They also have an assortment of coffees, but I hadn't tried any! Overall, if you're visiting and have the time or you're hosting a friend and they have the time, Tartine is a pleasant stop in the city. I'd recommend checking the high traffic times on google maps and trying to avoid that (10-12 on Sunday morning for example)!

Oh Tartine. First time I went, the coconut cream tart was out-of-this-world amazing. This time I got morning bun, lemon tart, and a dark chocolate tea cake. The line is long, even at 8am on Saturday, and moves quite slow. Compared to B. Patisserie the line moves about 2x-3x as slow, if anyone is curious about how long the wait may be. So if you've been to B. Patisserie and been through that line, you can roughly gauge how slow the line here will take you. Let's start with the lemon start, perhaps the most hyped item on yelp from this place. Is there any other item that receives more praise than the lemon tart here? I've come here multiple times and could never snag one so this time I got there bright and early at 8am. After taking a bite... *drumroll* ... it was a huge disappointment. This first thing that hit me was a metallic stainless-steel taste from the knife. Moving on from that it was a HUGE let down. Now, don't get me wrong I've had plenty of lemon tarts from other places before and thought Tartine's would be the absolute best given what everyone has said. That was not the case. The lemon cream was tart and sour, and not very sweet with a dollop of whipped cream (very lightly sweetened) on top. Combined, it was pretty good but the cream was slightly too rich. That itself wasn't the issue - overall it just didn't "WOW" like I was expecting it to. Would I get it again? No. I'd probably get the coconut cream tart again though - THAT was amazing. Let's move on to the other items. The morning bun was pretty good and the candied orange (orange zest?) definitely lifted the pastry up. The orange gives it a bright, refreshing flavor that makes it the perfect breakfast pastry. The chocolate tea cake was SO. F******. GOOD. It was NOT sweet at all which is PERFECT for me because I don't like anything that is too sweet. It had a very deep chocolately flavor (I believe they use Valrhona chocolate/cocoa powder - the best). This was definitely the star because of the flavor development they were able to get. It's a very dense cake that allows you to eat a little bit of it over the day.

    11/5/2016

    3 photos

    9 check-ins

    Oh Tartine. First time I went, the coconut cream tart was out-of-this-world amazing. This time I got morning bun, lemon tart, and a dark chocolate tea cake. The line is long, even at 8am on Saturday, and moves quite slow. Compared to B. Patisserie the line moves about 2x-3x as slow, if anyone is curious about how long the wait may be. So if you've been to B. Patisserie and been through that line, you can roughly gauge how slow the line here will take you.

    Let's start with the lemon start, perhaps the most hyped item on yelp from this place. Is there any other item that receives more praise than the lemon tart here? I've come here multiple times and could never snag one so this time I got there bright and early at 8am. After taking a bite... *drumroll* ... it was a huge disappointment. This first thing that hit me was a metallic stainless-steel taste from the knife. Moving on from that it was a HUGE let down. Now, don't get me wrong I've had plenty of lemon tarts from other places before and thought Tartine's would be the absolute best given what everyone has said. That was not the case.

    The lemon cream was tart and sour, and not very sweet with a dollop of whipped cream (very lightly sweetened) on top. Combined, it was pretty good but the cream was slightly too rich. That itself wasn't the issue - overall it just didn't "WOW" like I was expecting it to. Would I get it again? No. I'd probably get the coconut cream tart again though - THAT was amazing.

    Let's move on to the other items. The morning bun was pretty good and the candied orange (orange zest?) definitely lifted the pastry up. The orange gives it a bright, refreshing flavor that makes it the perfect breakfast pastry. The chocolate tea cake was SO. F******. GOOD. It was NOT sweet at all which is PERFECT for me because I don't like anything that is too sweet. It had a very deep chocolately flavor (I believe they use Valrhona chocolate/cocoa powder - the best). This was definitely the star because of the flavor development they were able to get. It's a very dense cake that allows you to eat a little bit of it over the day.
